'''Robin Friday''' (27 July 1952 – 22 December 1990) was an English [[Association football|football]]er who played professionally as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] during a career that lasted four years in the mid-1970s.{{ref label|career|A}} Born and raised in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London, Friday was scouted, but not retained, by four professional clubs during his teenage years. After appearing for local semi-professional sides in the [[Isthmian League]], he joined [[Charlie Hurley]]'s [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] Reading team in 1974. He quickly became a key player, and helped Reading to win [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] during the {{nobreak|[[1975–76 Football League|1975–76]]}} season.

Friday's on-field performances were regarded as excellent, and he won Reading's player of the year award in both of his full seasons there, as well as being the leading goal scorer. However, his habit of unsettling opponents through physical intimidation contributed to a heavily tarnished disciplinary record. Friday was also known off the field for his heavy smoking, drinking, womanising and drug-taking.

As his drug habit intensified, Friday's form began to dip in the first half of the [[1976–77 Football League|1976–77]] season, leading Reading to sell him to [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] side Cardiff City in December 1976. Friday travelled to join his new team by train, without a valid ticket and had to be bailed by Cardiff manager [[Jimmy Andrews]] before even signing for the club. He performed strongly on his debut, but afterwards his form declined and his personal life caused him to repeatedly miss matches altogether. Following a number of incidents, on and off the field&amp;nbsp;– including kicking [[Mark Lawrenson]] in the face {{nobreak|mid-game}}{{ref label|lawrensonkitbag|B|a}}&amp;nbsp;– Friday retired from football in December 1977, aged 25. He died in Acton in 1990, aged 38, after suffering a heart attack.

The strongest aspects of Friday's game were his ball skills, footballing intelligence and physical and mental strength. Andrews labelled Friday &quot;the complete centre-forward&quot;,&lt;ref name=biog192/&gt; and, along with numerous contemporaries, retrospectively rated Friday as good enough for the [[England national football team|England national team]]. Both because of his playing ability and personality, Friday remains an important figure to fans of both Reading and Cardiff, despite his short career: in a [[BBC]] poll held in 2004, he was voted the top &quot;all-time cult hero&quot; for both clubs. He has been voted Reading's best ever player three times, in 1999 and twice in 2007. Cardiff-based band [[Super Furry Animals]] dedicated their 1996 single ''[[The Man Don't Give a Fuck]]'' to his memory.

==Early life and semi-professional football==
===Childhood===
[[File:Griffin Park 1982 - geograph-2023521.jpg|thumb|The Friday brothers saw their first professional match at the age of two, at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]'s [[Griffin Park]] ground, pictured in 1982.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a soccer match in progress in front of a modest, single-tiered, British-style grandstand.]]
Robin Friday and his twin brother, Tony, were born in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London, on 27 July 1952. Their parents, Alf Friday, a driver for a laundry firm, and his wife Sheila, were both born in Acton and had married a year before, both aged 20, having met three years earlier. Sheila's father, Frederick Riding, had played professional football for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] before the Second World War. The Fridays lived with Sheila's family until moving into a [[Prefabricated home|prefab]] of their own in [[Acton Green, London|Acton Green]] when Robin and Tony were aged two; they later moved to a [[maisonette]] in [[South Acton, London|South Acton]] in 1962 when it was found that the prefab was sinking. Robin and Tony were later described by their mother as having been remarkably close, rarely arguing or fighting. A noticeable difference in personality was that Robin was shy, whereas Tony was more confident. The twins attended their first professional match at the age of two, when their father took them to a Brentford match at [[Griffin Park]]. From the age of four Alf took both boys to play football at a local park every afternoon.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog23&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=23–26}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Around the age of ten, Robin possessed notable ball-skills, and according to his father could flick an orange up onto his neck, balance it and then let it roll it back down his body and catch it on his foot. As well as football, Robin played cricket to a high standard, boxed and played tennis. Despite their many similarities and common interest in sports and football in particular, the twins were wildly different in academic terms: while Tony did well at school, Robin was uninterested and according to his brother &quot;was always [[wiktionary:bunk#Etymology 3|bunking off]], having [[wiktionary:bird#Etymology 1|birds]] around the park.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog26&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=26–28}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Robin was scouted by numerous London sides during his teenage years, joining [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]'s school of excellence at 12 or 13, then moving on to [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] aged 13 and then to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], with whom he attended the [[1967 FA Cup Final]]; as one of the club's youth players, he was part of the team's official party. However, Friday's individual style of play and refusal to change his game resulted in each of these clubs losing patience with him. The twin brothers joined a men's team, the Acton British Legion Reserves, aged 14, and in some matches would play alongside their father. Tony played in midfield, and Robin up front, but according to Tony his brother was better as a goalkeeper than a forward: &quot;He was a brilliant goalkeeper. He had no fear ... But he obviously preferred banging them in at the other end.&quot; Around this time Robin became interested in music, dancing and attending concerts; he also had a talent for drawing, but suddenly abandoned this interest at 15. Robin became more outgoing than his brother and started taking drugs in his mid-teens. He left school at 15, a year before Tony, and began training as a plasterer.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog28&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=28–32}}&lt;/ref&gt;
{{clear}}

===Borstal, first marriage and the Isthmian League===
Friday lasted two months as a plasterer before moving on to become first a van driver for a grocery firm, then a window cleaner. His laid-back attitude and indifference was already clear: in his father's words, &quot;he didn't care&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog32&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=32–33}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday regularly stole by this time, but despite numerous convictions, did not go to a detention centre until he was 16. Having been caught stealing what Tony recalled to be &quot;a car radio or something&quot;, he was released almost immediately because he suffered from [[asthma]]. However, after he re-offended three months later he was sent to [[Feltham (HM Prison)|Feltham]] [[Borstal]] where he served 14 months.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog34a&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=34}}&lt;/ref&gt; During his time there, Friday became stronger and fitter and also starred for the Borstal football team. He was selected for the prison league's all-star men's team, still aged 16, and allowed out of borstal to train and play with [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]'s youth team, for which he appeared three times in the [[South East Counties League]] during the 1968–69 season.&lt;ref name=biog34/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog42/&gt;

After his release, Friday returned to Acton and met a local [[Black British|black]] girl named Maxine Doughan, whom he made pregnant. The local controversy surrounding the [[Interracial marriage|interracial relationship]] caused the couple and their circle of friends to be isolated socially, and even led to a physical attack on the whole group one night in an Acton [[public house]]. Despite this, and the opposition by both sets of parents – Alf refused to even attend the wedding – they married, both aged 17.&lt;ref name=biog34/&gt; A daughter, Nicola, was born soon afterwards but Friday did not take his marital commitments seriously, continuing to womanise, drink heavily and take narcotics.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog34&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=34–35}}&lt;/ref&gt; A friend who played for [[Walthamstow Avenue F.C.|Walthamstow Avenue]], a semi-professional [[Isthmian League]] club from north-east London, took Friday along to training one day in early 1971. Friday played well enough for Walthamstow to sign him the same day on wages of [[Pound sterling|£]]10 per week. Many of his new team-mates were [[asphalt]]ers from east London, and Friday soon joined them in that trade.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog35&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=35–36}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{location map+ | Greater London |float=right |width=300 |caption=Locations of Friday's non-League clubs in relation to his home in [[Acton, London|Acton]], shown within [[Greater London]] |places=
{{location map~ | Greater London |lat=51.501664 |long=-0.2635 |label=&lt;span style=&quot;background-color:white;&quot;&gt;Friday's home ([[Acton, London|Acton]])|position=right}}
{{location map~ | Greater London |lat=51.591444 |long=-0.030503 |label=&lt;span style=&quot;background-color:white;&quot;&gt;[[Walthamstow Avenue F.C.|Walthamstow&amp;nbsp;Avenue]]|position=right}}
{{location map~ | Greater London |lat=51.515072 |long=-0.422233 |label=&lt;span style=&quot;background-color:white;&quot;&gt;[[Hayes F.C.|Hayes]]|position=right}}
{{location map~ | Greater London |lat=51.651698 |long=-0.063665 |label=&lt;span style=&quot;background-color:white;&quot;&gt;[[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]]|position=right}}
}}
Friday made his debut for Walthamstow on 27 March 1971, against [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]], coming off the bench to set up Walthamstow's equaliser. His first goal came on 17 April, when playing against [[Tooting &amp; Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting &amp; Mitcham]] he once again appeared as a substitute and scored a header late in the game. He joined west London club [[Hayes F.C.|Hayes]] in December 1971 after scoring twice against them in an Isthmian League match.&lt;ref name=hayesprofile/&gt; Hayes offered £30 per week, and were also based closer to his home in Acton. A near-fatal accident at work in July 1972 caused Friday to undergo extensive surgery; while working on a roof in [[Lambeth]], a [[Hoist (device)|hoist]] rope became stuck on the scaffold he was working on. The Hayes forward attempted to free the rope but fell and landed on a large spike – the spike went up through one of his buttocks, through his stomach and narrowly avoided a lung. Not only was Friday strong enough to pull himself off the spike, he recovered from his injuries within three months and returned to the Hayes team in October 1972.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog36&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=36–37}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Friday was known at Hayes for his excessive drinking, and on one occasion the team started a match a player short because Friday had not turned up. When he finally arrived, eighty minutes after kick-off, his intoxication was obvious. Nevertheless, he was sent onto the pitch with the match still goalless. The opposition paid him little attention and Friday scored a late winning goal.&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt; Hayes were drawn to play [[The Football League|Football League]] [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] club Reading in the [[FA Cup]]'s second round on 9 December 1972;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal
|title=Hayes
|work=Reading F.C. Official Programme
|publisher=[[Reading F.C.]]
|page=1
|date=1972-12-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; the team managed to draw 0–0 at Reading and earn the right to a [[Replay (sports)|replay]] at home, which they lost 1–0 three days later.&lt;ref name=&quot;replay1972&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/fa-cup/1972-1973/results/1972-12-12
|title=English FA Cup 1972–1973 : Results
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-09-17}}&lt;/ref&gt; Although Hayes had lost, the interest of Reading manager [[Charlie Hurley]] was piqued. Hurley travelled to Hayes more than once to watch Friday. Having researched the player's background, he was cautious about signing him, but was impressed all the same by his on-field performances.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog39&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=39}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[1972–73 in English football|1972–73]] season was Friday's most prolific non-League year in terms of goals.&lt;ref name=hayesprofile/&gt; He briefly joined [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]] early in the [[1973–74 in English football|1973–74]] season and actually scored against Hayes in an FA Cup tie before returning to west London in December 1973.&lt;ref name=&quot;hayesprofile&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=A–Z of Hayes FC: Friday, R – Fulker
|publisher=[[Hayes &amp; Yeading United F.C.]]
|first=Terry
|last=Hunt
|url=http://www.hyufc.com/history_files/friday-fulker.html
|accessdate=2011-05-12}}&lt;/ref&gt; Despite an approach from [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] side [[Watford F.C.|Watford]],&lt;ref name=biog42/&gt; the forward signed for Hurley's Reading side in January 1974 for £750.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog37&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=37–40}}&lt;/ref&gt; He had scored 46 goals in 67 appearances for Hayes over his two spells there,&lt;ref name=hayesprofile/&gt; but during his three Isthmian League seasons had been sent off seven times.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog114&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=114}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday signed as an amateur, meaning that although he would be contracted to Reading he would be able to continue to appear for Hayes and work as an asphalter in London; he would train part-time with Reading and play for their reserve team.&lt;ref name=biog39/&gt;

==Professional career==
===Reading===
====1973–74 season====
{{Quote box|align=left|width=30%|quote=In his very first training session they were playing a six-a-side game and Robin went around trying to kick as many of the established Reading players as he could. He must have put two or three out of the game. [Charlie] Hurley had to call him off ...|source=&lt;small&gt;Reading F.C. historian David Downs recounts Friday's first training session with Reading&lt;ref name=biog37/&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}

In Hurley's words, Friday &quot;trained like he played&quot;; &quot;he had no other way of playing.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog40&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=40}}&lt;/ref&gt; His new manager even had to take him out of training on occasion because of the injuries he would inflict on his own team-mates in his effort to win.&lt;ref name=biog37/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog40/&gt; By late January 1974, Reading were on a run of fourteen games with only two victories, while Friday had performed strongly in three reserve matches. Hurley registered the amateur forward to play in The Football League on 23 January 1974 and gave him his first-team debut four days later.&lt;ref name=biog40/&gt; Friday turned in a performance against [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] at [[Elm Park (stadium)|Elm Park]] that the ''[[Reading Post|Reading Evening Post]]'' called &quot;outstanding&quot; as Reading drew 3–3.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog41&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=41}}&lt;/ref&gt; The team then travelled to [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on 3 February, having not won away from home in four months. After Barnsley led 2–0 at half-time, Friday scored his first League goal with a header just after the break to make the score 2–1.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog43&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=43}}&lt;/ref&gt; Reading immediately offered a professional contract, which Friday signed on 6 February 1974.&lt;ref name=biog43/&gt; His new salary was half what he had earned as an asphalter.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog42&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=42}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Quote box|align=right|width=30%|quote=The team that has been transformed by Robin Friday has now scored a remarkable 16 goals in five games and the highlight of this joyous afternoon was a goal by Friday that was worth anyone's admission money on its own ...|source=&lt;small&gt;Excerpt from ''[[Reading Post|Reading Evening Post]]'' match report, 24 February 1974&lt;ref name=biog48/&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}
Friday's technical ability made him very popular among Reading supporters and pressmen alike. The ''Reading Evening Post'' report of Reading's 4–1 victory over [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] on 10 February 1974, Friday's first match as a professional, described his performance as &quot;sheer magic&quot; as he scored twice.&lt;ref name=biog44/&gt; The report also called Friday's first goal of the day &quot;glorious&quot;: he collected the ball wide on the left wing, took it past four Exeter defenders and then fired the ball low and hard into the opposite corner from the edge of the penalty area.&lt;ref name=biog44/&gt; Friday was conspicuous in the professional ranks for never wearing [[Shin guard|shin pads]], and for his resistance to physical harm; no matter how badly he was hurt he would always get up and continue.&lt;ref name=biog44/&gt; After sustaining a calf injury against Exeter, he returned for the team's next game, away at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] on 17 February. Friday was repeatedly and cynically fouled by the opposing players and sustained injuries necessitating five minutes on the sideline late in the first half. However, he recovered, returned to the game and set up both Reading goals as his side prevailed by a score of two goals to nil.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog44&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=44–47}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt; The team's next game, on 24 February 1974, was at home against [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], and with Friday playing a key role Reading won 5–0. In particular, Friday scored a goal after 17 minutes described by the ''Evening Post'' reporter as &quot;magical&quot;:&lt;ref name=biog48/&gt; with the score 1–0 to Reading, Friday received the ball near the edge of the penalty area, at a tight angle, and coolly kicked the ball with the outside of his boot low across goal, towards the far post. Although it appeared to be heading yards wide of the net, the ball suddenly curved in at the last possible moment – &quot;right around the goalie&quot;, in the words of Reading F.C. historian David Downs – and clipped the goalpost before nestling in the back of the net.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog48&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=48–49}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt;

{{Quote box|align=left|width=30%|quote=Blessed with awesome stamina, he ran riot outside football. He danced naked in clubs, naked in pubs. He openly smoked spliffs and dropped pills. He caroused until late at night and would then return to his flat and crank his beloved music up until dawn. Girls flocked to him and he couldn't resist. Men rushed to buy him drinks and he could not resist.|source=&lt;small&gt;Paulo Hewitt describes Friday in August 1997&lt;ref name=biog17/&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}
Despite his immediate impact on the pitch and the upturn in Reading's form, Friday's off-the-field activities unsettled some of his team-mates. Most tolerated his lifestyle because of his importance to the team, but some, particularly defender [[Tommy Youlden]], were sceptical.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog78&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=78}}&lt;/ref&gt; He drank extremely heavily, favouring American [[Colt 45 (malt liquor)|Colt 45]] malt liquor,&lt;ref name=&quot;biog47&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=47|quote=Rod Lewington: He drank lager. There was a very strong lager at the time called Colt 45 which is what he drank. I never saw him drink spirits. ... Alf Friday: He could drink Southern Comfort all night long. Sheila Friday: And he wouldn't be drunk.}}&lt;/ref&gt; and his antics during his drinking sessions caused many landlords to lose patience with him. For example, Friday was barred from [[Caversham, Berkshire|Caversham]]'s Crown public house after he ended a night there leaping between the tables and dancing on the bar.&lt;ref name=biog47/&gt; The Boar's Head in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] also banned him on ten separate occasions.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog17&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=17}}&lt;/ref&gt; One night, after the pubs closed, Friday and a friend, Rod Lewington, went to an all-night club called Churchill's where they could continue drinking. When they entered, Friday, wearing a long overcoat and [[Hobnail (footwear)|hobnail boots]], walked onto the dancefloor and removed the coat to reveal that he was wearing nothing underneath. He then began to dance, completely naked apart from the boots.&lt;ref name=biog64/&gt; Although Churchill's, described by Lewington as &quot;the worst club that has ever been in Reading&quot;, tolerated such behaviour,&lt;ref name=biog64/&gt; the town's fashionable Sindlesham Mill nightclub did not, regularly barring Friday for his bizarre activities, including a dance he invented called &quot;the elephant&quot; which consisted of turning the pockets of his jeans inside out and undoing his flies to expose himself.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog94&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=94}}&lt;/ref&gt; He and his friends would regularly drink all day,&lt;ref name=biog81/&gt; though he was able to exert some self-control; according to his friend Syd Simmonds, Friday would obey Hurley's instruction not to drink for 48 hours before each game.&lt;ref name=biog81/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog86&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=86|quote=Syd Simmonds: He [Friday] wasn't a heavy drinker. I probably drank more than him and I was a driver. ... And that stuff about him drinking before a game? Complete fantasy. ... Charlie Hurley: I told him, 'If at all possible, try never to drink two days before a game.' But I think that might have been asking a lot of him.}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, he would play his prized [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] records very loudly at any time of the day or night and take [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] with casual indifference.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog81&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=81|quote=Syd Simmonds: One night I came home and and on the coffee table was a big dinner plate with an [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|acid]] tab on it. ... 'We'll be all right,' he [Friday] said, 'Just do half each.'}}&lt;/ref&gt; Hurley attempted to calm Friday down by moving him into an apartment above the football club's elderly ex-groundsman, but to no avail: &quot;Even if it was three in the morning, the first thing would be to get the music playing,&quot; Simmonds later said. &quot;We had an old boy living below us ... the ex-groundsman at Reading. He was coming up to 80 and he had a dog's life in the flat. Pounding music, people knocking on the door, girls throwing stones at the windows. Poor old sod.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog64&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=64–68}}&lt;/ref&gt;

====1974–75 season====
[[File:Elm Park, the former home of Reading FC.jpg|thumb|Friday played home matches for [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at [[Elm Park (stadium)|Elm Park]], pictured in 1981.|alt=A colour shot of a soccer match in progress, taken from the terraced stand behind one of the goals. The terraced stand at the far end is without a roof, while the stand to the right is covered.]]
After Reading finished the [[1973–74 Football League|1973–74]] season in sixth position, one place higher than the previous year,&lt;ref name=rundlereading/&gt; Friday continued to play well during the [[1974–75 Football League|1974–75]] season. By September 1974 he was attracting the interest of [[Football League First Division|First Division]] sides [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]];&lt;ref name=biog68/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog69/&gt; the former had been following him since the game at Barnsley back in February, when he had still been an amateur.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog68&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=68}}&lt;/ref&gt; United had by this time sent [[Scout (sport)|scouts]] to see Friday six times&lt;ref name=biog68/&gt; and Arsenal manager [[Bertie Mee]] had personally attended Reading's 4–2 home win over [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 12 September,&lt;ref name=&quot;biog69&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=69}}&lt;/ref&gt; but no approach came from either team. After Reading despatched [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] 3–0 on 14 September 1974, Friday and forward partner [[Dick Habbin]] had scored six goals each and topped the Football League goalscoring charts.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog70&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=70}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, at the same time Friday's disciplinary record was becoming so bad that even the ''Evening Post'', usually favourable to him, criticised him on 30 September 1974, just after he had scored his first [[hat-trick]] for Reading in a 4–1 victory over [[Southport F.C.|Southport]].&lt;ref name=biog72/&gt; He was the Football League's joint top scorer by this time with nine goals, but he had also already been booked three times that season and the ''Post'' argued that by constantly risking suspension he was letting the team down. Under the system then used, the three bookings gave him an automatic two-match suspension. The article argued that missing games because of &quot;completely unnecessary&quot; and &quot;stupid&quot; infractions amounted to selling the club short.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog72&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=72–73}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Friday's behaviour on Reading away trips was unpredictable and erratic: in the words of team-mate [[John Murray (English footballer)|John Murray]], &quot;Some of the things he did were funny but other times they were just mad.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog117/&gt; On the way back from one away match, the team bus pulled over for Friday to go to the toilet and on getting off the coach the forward noticed that they were beside a cemetery. Friday jumped over the wall and stole some stone angels from a grave, intending to place them beside club chairman Frank Waller, who was sleeping on the coach. When he returned, however, Hurley sternly told him that &quot;you must never ever desecrate a graveyard&quot;, causing the forward to obediently return the statues.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog108&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=108}}&lt;/ref&gt; On another occasion he reacted to the news that a team-mate had smuggled a girl into his hotel room by kicking the door in. Later on the same night he walked into the bar carrying a swan that he had found in the hotel grounds.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog117&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=117}}&lt;/ref&gt;

During an FA Cup tie away against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on 23 November, Friday began to have trouble breathing and despite leaving the game for five minutes to recuperate with an [[inhaler]] was eventually forced to come off for good, coughing violently.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog84&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=84}}&lt;/ref&gt; After recovering from what was reported to be a chest infection,&lt;ref name=biog84/&gt; he returned to the team on 28 December, having missed four matches, and marked his return with his side's only goal in a 3–1 home defeat to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]].&lt;ref name=&quot;biog87&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=87}}&lt;/ref&gt; Reading dropped to 12th place on 6 January 1975, and were only three points above the re-election places; however, by the time they took on [[Workington A.F.C.|Workington]] at home on 3 February they had risen to 10th.&lt;ref name=&quot;stattoworkington&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-four-old/1974-1975/table/1975-02-01
|title=English Division Four (old) 1974–1975 : Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; Reading won 3–0, with Friday scoring the third goal with a spectacular header: &quot;Diving full length barely a foot off the ground, Friday risked life and limb to head home a truly memorable goal&quot;, wrote the ''Evening Post'' match reporter. &quot;True to form, he had to spoil things for himself by getting booked three minutes later.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog90&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=90}}&lt;/ref&gt; This victory marked the beginning of a run of six wins out of seven games, after which the side was once again challenging for [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the third tier, hovering between sixth and eighth place for the rest of the season.&lt;ref name=&quot;statto75finale&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/reading/1974-1975/results
|title=Reading 1974–1975 : Results
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; By 11 April promotion looked improbable, but Friday was still overjoyed after scoring the last-minute winner in Reading's 2–1 victory over [[Rochdale F.C.|Rochdale]]. In celebration he ran behind the net and kissed a policeman.&lt;ref name=biog96/&gt; &quot;The policeman looked so cold and fed up standing there,&quot; explained the Reading forward, publicly, &quot;that I decided to cheer him up a bit.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog96/&gt; However, in the dressing room after the game he said, privately, that he wished he hadn't done it &quot;because I hate coppers so much.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog96&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=96–97}}&lt;/ref&gt; Reading eventually finished the 1974–75 season in seventh place, five points behind the promoted teams.&lt;ref name=&quot;statto75final&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-four-old/1974-1975/table/1975-04-26
|title=English Division Four (old) 1974–1975 : Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday was the club's top scorer for the season, with 18 league goals and 20 overall,&lt;ref name=sedunary/&gt; and was voted its player of the year.&lt;ref name=honoured/&gt;

====1975–76 season====
{{Quote box|align=left|width=30%|quote=His [Friday's] face looks as though it had been trampled on by a rugby squad and that was before the game. Friday's explanation: 'Me missus hit me with a can of beans.'|source=&lt;small&gt;Extract from ''[[Reading Evening Post]]'' match report, 13 September 1975&lt;ref name=&quot;biog102&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=102}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}

Friday's fine form continued into the [[1975–76 Football League|1975–76]] season; after their 4–2 victory over [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on 23 September 1975, Reading were top of the Fourth Division having just won four games in a row.&lt;ref name=&quot;statto7576results&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/reading/1975-1976/results
|title=Reading 1975–1976 : Results
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday, meanwhile, was the club's top scorer. The next game was against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on the 27th, and although Reading won 2–1 Friday was sent off after 79 minutes. By this time the forward was overwhelmingly popular among Reading's fans, to whom he endeared himself by performing a lap of honour after each goal he scored.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog102a&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=102–104}}&lt;/ref&gt; A month later, after two wins, two defeats and a draw during October, the team was fourth in the table.&lt;ref name=statto7576results/&gt; Friday, meanwhile, was arrested after the evening match away at [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] on 20 October, accused of using obscene language outside a [[Newport]] nightclub.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog110&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=110–111}}&lt;/ref&gt; At his appearance before magistrates in Newport on 17 November, he pleaded not guilty, representing himself, and was acquitted.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog115&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=115}}&lt;/ref&gt; Performing strongly for Reading and scoring regularly, he began to attract serious interest from other clubs. &quot;Friday is, of course, much more than Reading's top scorer and best striker,&quot; wrote the ''Evening Post'' on 3 November 1975. &quot;He is the most vital cog in the team, and last week I understand Reading turned down a £60,000 bid from [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] involving [[Wales national football team|Welsh]] international [[Derek Shallis]].&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog112&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=112}}&lt;/ref&gt; By the new year, Reading were third in the table, on course for promotion and two points behind league leaders [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].&lt;ref name=&quot;statto760103&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-four-old/1975-1976/table/1976-01-03
|title=English Division Four (old) 1975–1976 : Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt;

After Reading went four games without a win starting on 24 January 1976, a late goal from Friday ended this run on 25 February, in a home match against Hartlepool United; twelve minutes from time, he collected a pass from [[Stewart Henderson]] and neatly placed the ball past the goalkeeper from the edge of the penalty area. &quot;One is increasingly under the impression,&quot; the ''Evening Post'' reported, &quot;that if Friday was out for some time through injury the Reading team would fall to pieces.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog126&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=126–127}}&lt;/ref&gt; Led by the free-scoring Friday, the side continued its push for promotion; fourth or higher would be enough to go up. A vital fixture on 31 March 1976 pitted fourth-placed Reading at home against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]], who occupied third spot;&lt;ref name=&quot;stattotranmere&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1976-03-31
|title=Results : Wednesday 31st March 1976
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; internationally-experienced referee [[Clive Thomas]] took charge of the game. Friday, who had already scored 18 goals that season, rose to the occasion with an effort that has been described by many sources as one of the best ever scored.&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;honoured&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=Robin Friday honoured
|publisher=Reading F.C.
|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10306~1182761,00.html
|date=2007-12-04
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog130&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=130–131}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;mirror19760401&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
 | date = 1976-04-01
 | title = Friday rocket leads the lot
 | page = 31
 | first = Mike
 | last = Ramsbottom
 | journal=[[Daily Mirror]]
 | publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]
 | location = London}}&lt;/ref&gt;

With the score 2–0 to Reading, goalkeeper [[Steve Death]] threw the ball to right back [[Gary Peters (footballer)|Gary Peters]], who spotted Friday standing near the left-hand corner of the opposing penalty area. Peters passed high and diagonally across the pitch towards his forward, who jumped into the air and used his chest to cushion the ball and knock it into the air with his back to goal, about 25 yards away from the net. As Friday landed, he ferociously powered the ball towards goal, kicking over his shoulder and turning after the ball had gone. The shot flew straight into the top-right-hand corner of the net, stunning the crowd, players and referee Thomas, who put his hands over his head in disbelief. &quot;I'll never forget it,&quot; Thomas recalled, &quot;It was the sheer ferocity of the shot on the volley ... over his shoulder. ... If it hadn't gone into the top corner of the net it would have broken the goalpost. Even up against the likes of [[Pelé]] and [[Johan Cruyff|Cruyff]], that rates as the best goal I have ever seen.&quot; Reading went on to win the game 5–0.{{ref label|goaltranmere|C}} When Thomas told Friday after the game that he had never seen a better goal, the Londoner replied, &quot;Really? You should come down here more often, I do that every week.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog131&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=131}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:The Abbey Stadium.jpg|thumb|Reading secured promotion at [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]'s [[Abbey Stadium]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' on 22 April 1976.|alt=A colour photograph of a typical English lower-league grandstand, marked &quot;Cambridge United Football Club&quot;.]]
Reading moved to within one point of promotion on 20 April 1976 with a 1–0 home victory over [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. Friday set up the game's only goal, beating three players before hitting the post with his shot; [[Ray Hiron]] scored from the rebound.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog134&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=134}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday scored a powerful left-footed volley during the first half of a 2–2 draw away against [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] two days later. The result secured Third Division football for Reading.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog134a&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=134–135}}&lt;/ref&gt; At the celebratory dinner after the game, Reading [[captain (sports)|captain]] [[Gordon Cumming (footballer)|Gordon Cumming]] saw some fluted wine glasses, and voiced his admiration: &quot;I wouldn't mind a few of them for home,&quot; he said. &quot;Give us a few minutes and I'll get them for you,&quot; replied Friday. Going around the dining room and picking them off the tables, he stole a whole boxful of the glasses, which he managed to sneak out of the hotel and onto the team coach, but much to Cumming's annoyance he then decided to keep them for himself.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog135&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=135–136}}&lt;/ref&gt; With 22 goals for the year, 21 in the league,&lt;ref name=sedunary/&gt; Friday was once more Reading's top goalscorer and for the second consecutive season the team's player of the year.&lt;ref name=honoured/&gt;

After Reading were promoted, Waller met with the players on 4 June 1976 to discuss their contracts for the [[1976–77 Football League|1976–77]] season. The wages offered to the Reading players were far lower than they had been expecting, causing the team's morale to fall drastically. &quot;We got screwed by the club,&quot; midfielder [[Eamon Dunphy]] later claimed. &quot;We didn't get what we had been promised.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog138&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=138–139|quote=Eamon Dunphy: When we [Reading] got promotion we [the players] got screwed by the club. We didn't get what we had been promised. They [the board] acted very badly. At that stage the whole team lost faith in the board and in Hurley and in the club. ... At that stage morale plummeted. For Robin, that was his excuse to go back to living wild...}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday was so offended by the low salary offered that he handed in a transfer request, telling the ''Evening Post'' that the club's directors clearly did not share his ambition. &quot;They would be happy to stroll along in the bottom half of the Third Division forever,&quot; he said.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog139&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=139–140}}&lt;/ref&gt; The row over the new contracts continued throughout the off-season, while Friday planned his second wedding; he had been formally divorced from Maxine after years of separation, and subsequently engaged to Liza Deimel, a Reading-born university graduate.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog121&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=121}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the pay dispute was settled on 5 August, the couple were married in Reading three days later.&lt;ref name=biog140/&gt; The wedding was filmed by [[Southern Television]], before whose cameras Friday, wearing an open-necked tiger-skin-pattern shirt, brown velvet suit and snakeskin boots, sat on the steps of the church and rolled a [[Joint (cannabis)|joint]]. Friday had invited about two hundred people, mostly friends and relatives from London, who joined in the drinking and drug-taking and ending up fighting each other and stealing the couple's wedding presents, one of which was a large quantity of [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]]. Liza later called the wedding &quot;the most hilarious thing ever&quot;. &quot;I have been to a few weddings,&quot; recalled Rod Lewington, &quot;but never one like that.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog140&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=140–141}}&lt;/ref&gt;

====1976–77 season (to 30 December 1976)====

&quot;He lost his way when we got promotion,&quot; Hurley later reflected. &quot;He really must have celebrated all through the summer.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog142&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=142}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday reported back for pre-season training in bad condition, and although Hurley claimed that Friday was trying hard to regain fitness, the forward was having trouble with his asthma, had lost some of his pace and was obviously unfit.&lt;ref name=biog142/&gt; Although his performances during August quickly improved, they were still not up to his previous standard and the ''Evening Post'' revealed on the 30th that Reading were preparing to sell him &quot;to a First Division club&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog144&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=144}}&lt;/ref&gt; After scoring in two successive Reading home wins on 4 and 7 September, against [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] and [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] respectively,&lt;ref name=biog144/&gt; Friday took part in a third consecutive victory on the 13th, away against [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]].&lt;ref name=&quot;biog145&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=145}}&lt;/ref&gt; After this he missed two matches, according to the ''Post'' because he was suffering from [[influenza|flu]],&lt;ref name=&quot;biog146&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=146}}&lt;/ref&gt; and when he returned to the team was far from his best; &quot;Suddenly he had lost a yard and his control of the ball was not as good,&quot; Hurley recalled.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog147&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=147}}&lt;/ref&gt; Hurley was by now aware that his forward was using drugs, and attempted to keep his player's habit a secret while he patiently worked to bring him back around.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog147a&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=147–148}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, Friday began to regularly miss training and Hurley's subtlety was misinterpreted as inaction by the other Reading players, who became unsettled and complained about Friday's conduct.&lt;ref name=biog147a/&gt; The club became increasingly minded to sell him, but although top-flight clubs [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] were interested, they were reluctant to buy because of Friday's temperament; in Downs's words, &quot;They weren't sure they could handle him.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog147a/&gt; By the end of October 1976, Hurley had given up on attempting to rehabilitate his player, believing that the only solution was to sell him to a bigger team. Friday was made available for transfer, at his own request, on 28 October.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog148&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=148–149}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Quote box|align=left|width=30%|quote=The [Reading] squad needs you but I owe it to the club because I can't have you using drugs. ... If ''I'' know you're using drugs it won't take ''them'' [the major clubs] long to find out. You have got to get your act together. Or I'll have to give you a [[Free transfer (football)|free transfer]]. |source=&lt;small&gt;[[Charlie Hurley]], to Robin Friday, in late 1976&lt;ref name=&quot;biog148&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=148}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}
Friday was watched by other clubs throughout November and December 1976, but although he performed well in some games, including a 1–1 draw away at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 6 November in which he scored his team's only goal,&lt;ref name=&quot;biog150&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=150}}&lt;/ref&gt; he was poor in others. After being marked out of the game during Reading's 4–0 loss away against [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 8 November, he was substituted. &quot;Coincidence or not&quot;, wrote the ''Evening Post'', &quot;when Friday left, so did half a dozen managers and scouts.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog150/&gt; Friday was so angry at his team's performance that he broke into the Mansfield dressing room and defecated in the team bath.&lt;ref name=biog150/&gt; Reading's asking price stood at £50,000, and the first transfer offer came from [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] side Cardiff City around mid-December. Cardiff boss [[Jimmy Andrews]] bid £28,000,&lt;ref name=crooks45/&gt; half of his offer a year before, which Reading's directors accepted, wanting the troublesome player off their hands as quickly as possible.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog152&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=152}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=biog153/&gt; Friday was reluctant to go to the Welsh club, saying that it was too far from home, that he wanted to go to a First Division team and that he wanted more money than was being offered;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog153&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=153}}&lt;/ref&gt; however, when Hurley told him that unless he went to Cardiff he would be [[Free transfer (football)|released]], he agreed and travelled to Wales on 30 December 1976.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog153a&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=153–155}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Cardiff City===
====1976–77 season (from 30 December 1976)====
[[File:Cardiff General.jpg|thumb|While on his way to sign for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], Friday arrived at [[Cardiff Central railway station]], seen here in 1970, without a valid ticket and was arrested.|alt=A black-and-white photograph of a railway platform. Two trains stand side-by-side on the image's right while a sign on the platform reads &quot;Cardiff (General)&quot;. A formally-dressed gentleman stands on the platform, looking away from the viewer. A briefcase, presumably his, rests on a small trolley beside him.]]
On arrival at [[Cardiff Central railway station]], Friday was arrested by the [[British Transport Police]] for having travelled from Reading with only a [[platform ticket]].&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt;&lt;ref name=badboys/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog157&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=157}}&lt;/ref&gt; Andrews bailed his new player out of police custody and took him to [[Ninian Park]] to sign the contract.&lt;ref name=biog157/&gt; Despite the manner of Friday's arrival, and although he knew there &quot;had to be something wrong with him&quot;, the Cardiff manager was still happy with his purchase, describing the £28,000 transfer as &quot;an absolute steal&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog156&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=156}}&lt;/ref&gt; After a long night of drinking the night before his Cardiff debut, Friday lined up against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 1 January 1977. The Fulham defence included former [[England national football team|England]] [[List of England national football team captains|captain]] [[Bobby Moore]], but Friday marked his first match for the Welsh club with two goals; he also squeezed Moore's testicles during the game as Cardiff won 3–0.&lt;ref name=crooks45/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Hewitt&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|last=Hewitt
|year=2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Andrews was so happy with Friday's performance that he phoned Hurley two days later, on Monday morning. &quot;Oh, Charlie,&quot; Andrews gushed, &quot;he was magnificent. He tore them inside out. ... Moore was chasing him all over the place.&quot; The Cardiff manager continued to heap praise on his new acquisition until Hurley finally stopped him. &quot;Jimmy, you've only had him four days,&quot; he warned, sombrely: &quot;Give it a few months...&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog161&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=161–162}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Friday's form declined after his strong debut and his personal life remained troubled and chaotic, leading him to vanish regularly and miss Cardiff matches. Although he was supposed to be living in [[Bristol]], his manager would often find on visiting his house that he had been elsewhere for weeks.&lt;ref name=crooks45/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;cardiffhistory&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=Post Scoular: From Friday to Ford (1974–1989)
|publisher=[[Cardiff City F.C.]]
|url=http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/page/ClubHistory/0,,10335~61946,00.html
|date=2011-03-18
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;stattofulham&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1977-01-01
|title=Results : Saturday 1st January 1977
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; Leslie Hamilton, the Cardiff club doctor, later said that he had believed at the time that Andrews was being far too soft on Friday; indeed, according to team-mate [[Paul Went]], the forward would simply leave after each match and not be heard of until he returned for the next game. &quot;He wouldn't even bother to have a shower,&quot; Went later said, in an interview. &quot;He'd just get dressed, take his carrier-bag with his dry martini and he'd go – no explanation.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog171&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=171–173}}&lt;/ref&gt;

While Hurley had been able to command Friday's respect, it soon became clear that Andrews was unable to control him and that the Londoner disliked his new manager.&lt;ref name=biog164/&gt; Indeed, soon after moving to Cardiff, Friday appeared one day in Hurley's office at Elm Park asking to come back to Reading. &quot;He still called me boss,&quot; Hurley recalled. &quot;I can't play for that little bastard,&quot; Friday told Hurley, referring to Andrews. &quot;You're the one who seems to be able to get me right. Can I come back to you?&quot; Hurley replied that although he would be happy to have Friday back on the team, the club could not afford to repay the £28,000 transfer fee to Cardiff, so he would have to go back and continue playing there.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog164&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=164–165}}&lt;/ref&gt; Unhappy living so far from home, Friday began to travel back to London at weekends; he avoided paying rail fares by knocking on locked toilet doors and shouting, &quot;Tickets, please!&quot;, pretending to be the ticket inspector. When the occupant passed his ticket under the door to be checked, Friday would pick it up, walk off and use it for himself.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog159&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=159}}&lt;/ref&gt; Paul Went also recalled an incident during training when he had thrown a ball out from goal and accidentally hit Friday on the back of the head. A player standing near the forward started laughing, leading Friday to conclude that he had thrown the ball. Friday viciously punched the laughing player in the jaw, striking him with such force that he wore a [[Cervical collar|neck brace]] for two weeks afterwards.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog158&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=158–159}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Late in Friday's first season in Wales, Cardiff took on [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on 16 April 1977. Cardiff were in the [[promotion and relegation|relegation]] zone and had not won in seven games, while Luton were fifth in the table and challenging for promotion.&lt;ref name=&quot;stattocardiff1&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-two-old/1976-1977/table/1977-04-11
|title=English Division Two (old) 1976–1977 : Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;stattocardiff2&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/cardiff-city/1976-1977/results
|title=Cardiff City 1976–1977 : Results
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; After clashing repeatedly early in the match with Luton goalkeeper [[Milija Aleksic]], Friday was lectured by the referee for a high tackle on the goalkeeper in the 36th minute. Friday held out a hand to apologise, but Aleksic reacted angrily. When the free kick was taken, Friday ran back, stole the ball from Luton defender [[John Faulkner (footballer)|John Faulkner]], broke away, rounded Aleksic and slotted the ball past him into the net. In celebration, Friday turned towards the goalkeeper and gave him the [[V sign#V sign as an insult|V-sign]].&lt;ref name=&quot;swecho19770418&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
 | date = 1977-04-18
 | title = V-sign Friday says &quot;I'm not a villain&quot;
 | page = 18
 | first = Karl
 | last = Woodward
 | journal=[[South Wales Echo]]
 | publisher=[[Media Wales|Western Mail &amp; Echo Ltd]]
 | location = [[Cardiff]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cardiff won the match 4–2 and at the end of the season avoided relegation to the third tier only on [[goal difference]].&lt;ref name=stattocardiff2/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;rundlecardiff&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.fchd.btinternet.co.uk/CARDIFFC.HTM
|title=Football Club History Database – Cardiff City
|publisher=Football Club History Database
|first=Richard
|last=Rundle
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;stattocardiff3&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/cardiff-city/1976-1977/table
|title=Cardiff City 1976–1977 : English Division Two (old) Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; Meanwhile, without Friday, Reading were relegated back to the Fourth Division by one point.&lt;ref name=rundlereading/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;stattoreading&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/reading/1976-1977/table
|title=Reading 1976–1977 : English Division Three (old) Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-04-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday's actions became even stranger during his time at Cardiff; after they lost the second leg of the [[Welsh Cup]] final 3–0 to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on 18 May 1977,{{ref label|cupfinal|D}} the players and staff were awoken in the middle of the night by loud bangs coming from below their rooms. The cause was found to be Friday, standing on the hotel's snooker table in his underpants and throwing the balls around the room in fury.&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt;

====1977–78 season====
[[File:Goldstone Ground - geograph-1220106.jpg|thumb|left|Friday's penultimate professional match was played at [[Brighton &amp; Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton &amp; Hove Albion]]'s [[Goldstone Ground]], pictured here in 1976.|alt=A colour photograph, taken from behind a goal net, of a roofed English-style grandstand, filled with people. ]]
After failing to turn up for pre-season training with Cardiff before the [[1977–78 Football League|1977–78]] season,&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt; Friday was reported to be in a London hospital suffering from an unknown virus which had caused him to lose {{convert|2|st|kg|lk=on}} in weight. When he suddenly appeared in Cardiff for training in October, two months into the season, he claimed to have been suffering from [[hepatitis]], but medical tests disproved this.&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt; Andrews told the local press that on arrival Friday had looked &quot;like the fittest player in the world&quot;, and hoping to avoid further disappearances persuaded a reluctant Friday to move from Bristol to Cardiff.&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt; He returned to the team for the away match at [[Brighton &amp; Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton &amp; Hove Albion]] on 29 October 1977, with Cardiff once again in the relegation zone, in 20th place on goal difference.&lt;ref name=&quot;stattocardiff291077&quot;&gt;{{cite web
|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-two-old/1977-1978/table/1977-10-29
|title=English Division Two (old) 1977–1978 : Table
|publisher=Statto
|accessdate=2011-05-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday was marked during the game by [[Mark Lawrenson]], who so frustrated the Cardiff forward with his close attention that Friday waited for Lawrenson to attempt a slide tackle and then kicked him in the face.&lt;ref name=Titford46/&gt; After receiving a [[red card (sports)|red card]], Friday left the ground with the game still going on; according to legend, before leaving he broke into the Brighton dressing room and defecated in Lawrenson's kit bag.{{ref label|lawrensonkitbag|B|b}} Cardiff eventually lost 4–0.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog174&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=174–175}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=mirror19771031/&gt; &quot;I am sick and tired of it,&quot; Andrews told the ''[[South Wales Echo]]'' on 1 November. &quot;To be sent off in his first game back is as much as a man can stand.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog175/&gt; Friday was [[Transfer market#Transfer list|transfer-listed]] and served a three-match suspension before making his final appearance on 10 December in Cardiff's 6–3 away defeat against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]]. Liza was by now the mother of Friday's second daughter, Arabella, but around this time began divorce proceedings. Friday claimed that he had had enough of people telling him what to do,&lt;ref name=biog175/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |last=Brown |year=2004 |page=45}}&lt;/ref&gt; and walked into Andrews's office on 20 December 1977 to announce that he was retiring from professional football. The club promptly released him and cancelled his contract.&lt;ref name=crooks45/&gt;&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;&lt;ref name=cardiffhistory/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog175&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=175}}&lt;/ref&gt;
{{clear}}

==Post-retirement==
{{Quote box|align=right|width=30%|quote=At the funeral I have never seen so many people ... When we got to the flat, the stairs and corridors leading to his mum's front door were packed with people.|source=&lt;small&gt;Liza Friday, second wife&lt;ref name=&quot;biog184&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=184}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;/small&gt;|quoted = 1}}
After retiring, Friday moved back to London and returned to work as an asphalter and decorator.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog175&quot;/&gt; Soon after Friday left Cardiff, Reading manager [[Maurice Evans (footballer)|Maurice Evans]] was presented with a petition, signed by 3,000 supporters, requesting that he attempt to re-sign Friday. Evans contacted Friday and told him: &quot;If you would just settle down for three or four years, you could play for England.&quot; Friday replied with the question &quot;How old are you?&quot;, and after Evans answered, continued: &quot;I'm half your age and I've lived twice your life.&quot; Evans reflected, &quot;You may well be right.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;roughley&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|last=Roughley
|year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog187&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=187–188}}&lt;/ref&gt; Friday trained with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] during the [[1978–79 Football League|1978–79]] pre-season, but after regaining his fitness suddenly changed his mind and stopped coming to training. He married for a third time in 1980, but was divorced again within three years. After a short time living back with his parents in Acton, Friday's family secured him a [[housing association]] flat in the area.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog178&quot;&gt;{{cite book| last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|pages=178–181}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford26&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=26
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; He served prison time during the 1980s for impersonating a police officer and confiscating people's drugs,&lt;ref name=&quot;biog19&quot;&gt;{{cite book| last1=McGuigan|last2=Hewitt|year=1997|page=19}}&lt;/ref&gt; and was found dead in his Acton flat on 22 December 1990 at the age of 38, having suffered a fatal heart attack.&lt;ref name=honoured/&gt; Biographer Paolo Hewitt claimed the incident to be the result of &quot;a suspected heroin overdose&quot;.&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt;

==Style of play and legacy==
[[File:Themandontgiveafuck.jpg|thumb|left|Friday's 1977 altercation with [[Milija Aleksic]] is depicted on the cover of [[Super Furry Animals]]' 1996 single ''[[The Man Don't Give a Fuck]]'', which was dedicated to his memory.&lt;ref name=Linernotes1/&gt;|alt=A dark-haired man in blue, white and yellow soccer attire scowls as he turns to his left, holding the index and middle fingers up on his right hand, his palm facing inwards. The hand points to an out-of-image figure, but appears to be pointing to the viewer. &quot;Super Furry Animals&quot; is rendered in yellow and red text across the top, while along the bottom the single's title is partially given: &quot;The Man Don't Give a ****&quot;. The final word is obscured by a sticker, which itself claims that the word is used 50 times during the song.]]
Friday is widely regarded as an unsung talent; a latterly-applied nickname, &quot;the greatest footballer you never saw&quot;,&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford15&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=15
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; was used as the title of his 1997 biography, co-written by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] [[bassist|bass player]] [[Paul McGuigan (musician)|Paul McGuigan]] and Hewitt.&lt;ref name=&quot;mcguigantitle&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=1}}&lt;/ref&gt; Both as a player and a personality, Friday remains a major figure for both of his professional clubs. [[BBC Radio Berkshire]] Sports Editor [[Tim Dellor]], speaking in 2010, emphasised the importance of Friday's charisma to his contemporary and retrospective appeal, a point which was also highlighted by his second wife, Liza, who likened his personal charm to that of &quot;a [[Pied Piper of Hamelin|pied piper]]&quot;. In terms of significance to Reading F.C., Dellor stated that Friday was the team's &quot;very own [[George Best]]&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;bbcberks2010&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|last=Minard
|year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cardiff-based band [[Super Furry Animals]] used a photograph of him giving the V-sign to Aleksic in 1977 for the artwork of their 1996 single ''[[The Man Don't Give a Fuck]]'', which was dedicated to his memory &quot;and his stand against the 'Man'&quot;.&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;&lt;ref name=Linernotes1&gt;{{cite album-notes
|title=The Man Don't Give a Fuck
|albumlink=The Man Don't Give a Fuck
|artist=[[Super Furry Animals]]
|year=1996
|format=CD booklet
|publisher=[[Creation Records]]
|publisherid=CRESCD247
|location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford9&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=9
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; After winning the title of &quot;Player of the Millennium&quot; from Reading in 1999,&lt;ref name=&quot;playerofmillennium&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=Player Of The Millennium vote
|publisher=Reading F.C.
|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/page/History/0,,10306~70546,00.html
|date=2008-09-05
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; he was voted the top &quot;all-time cult hero&quot; for both Reading and Cardiff in a 2004 [[BBC]] poll;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
|title=Cardiff City's cult heroes
|publisher=BBC  
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/football_focus/4082355.stm
|date=2004-12-10
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
|title=Reading's cult heroes
|publisher=BBC  
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/football_focus/3656828.stm
|date=2004-09-16
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; with similar polls taking place at each [[Premier League]] and [[The Football League|Football League]] club, he was the only player to appear in the top three for two different sides.&lt;ref name=Titford21/&gt; In 2007, a poll of fans run by Reading resulted in his once more being named the club's best ever.&lt;ref name=honoured/&gt; Later that year, when the [[Professional Footballers' Association]] (PFA) canvassed Reading supporters for their all-time favourite, Friday won yet again.&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford21&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=21
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;localhero&quot;&gt;{{cite news
| title = Best footballers: Shearer a hero on two fronts
| url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2328937/Best-footballers-Shearer-a-hero-on-two-fronts.html
| first = Martin
| last = Smith
| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher = Telegraph Media Group
| date = 2007-12-09
| accessdate = 2011-07-14
| location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt; In a parallel PFA survey, Cardiff fans chose one of Friday's former team-mates, [[Wales national football team|Wales]] international defender [[Phil Dwyer]].&lt;ref name=localhero/&gt; Friday was ranked first in [[Channel 4]]'s list of football &quot;bad boys&quot; in August 2007,&lt;ref name=badboys/&gt; while ''[[Football365]]'' placed him at eighth place in a 2010 list of &quot;wasted talents&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;f365&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=F365's Top Ten Wasted Talents
|work=[[Football365]]
|publisher=[[365 Media Group]]
|location=[[Leeds]]
|first=Nick
|last=Miller
|url=http://www.football365.com/news/8750/6441275
|date=2010-10-12
|accessdate=2011-06-02}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Friday's style of play was based around his exceptional ball skills, described by Cardiff doctor Leslie Hamilton as &quot;absolutely fabulous&quot;,&lt;ref name=biog176/&gt; and his instinctive footballing vision, which enabled him both to execute flamboyant individual moves and to create attacks for his team-mates. Jimmy Andrews, his manager at Cardiff, later called Friday &quot;the complete centre-forward&quot; and placed him on a par with [[Alan Shearer]],&lt;ref name=biog192/&gt; while Maurice Evans claimed that he could have played for England,&lt;ref name=biog188/&gt; and was at least on a level with international strikers he had worked with such as [[John Aldridge]] and [[Dean Saunders]].&lt;ref name=&quot;biog189&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=189}}&lt;/ref&gt; This attitude was also held by Hamilton and Friday's Reading team-mate [[John Murray (English footballer)|John Murray]], both of whom firmly declared in separate interviews that Friday would have been good enough for the England team had he &quot;sorted his head out&quot;, in Hamilton's words.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog176&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| pages=176–177}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog188&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=188}}&lt;/ref&gt; A natural goalscoring forward, Friday was also unselfish and would take just as much pleasure out of setting up a goal scored by a team-mate as netting one himself. He possessed fine ball control and dribbling skills, and could also shoot with both great power and sharp accuracy.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog14&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=14}}&lt;/ref&gt; The strong physical aspect of his game and exceptionally competitive, combative spirit combined with all of this to create a formidable forward player – such was his ability that his arrival transformed Reading into one of the division's best sides in a matter of weeks.&lt;ref name=biog48/&gt; Writing in 2010, Roger Titford stressed Friday's immediate and profound impact on the Reading team as a key factor in his lasting popularity: &quot;It was like the comic-book stories that kids from Robin's era would have read&quot;, he wrote. &quot;He was a ready-made star.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford27&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=27
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On top of his technical talent, Friday was physically very strong and able to withstand sustained blows or injuries. According to Hamilton, he was also uncommonly fit despite his lifestyle.&lt;ref name=biog176/&gt; He boasted an exceptional work-rate, which Dwyer recalled gave any side including him a strong boost: &quot;When he was in the line-up you'd have a centre-forward ''and'' a centre-half; not only would he be up there running them ragged, but when it broke down he'd be the first person to start tackling back.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog173&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=173}}&lt;/ref&gt; He was assisted in this by a smooth and effective sliding tackle which despite all of Friday's attacking skills Hurley considered one of the strongest parts of his game. Reading F.C. historian David Downs described Friday's style of play as &quot;really quite bizarre. It was more or less Robin standing in the middle and saying 'Give me the ball and I'll see what I can do with it'.&quot; On receiving the ball, he would then turn and either take on the opposing defence single-handed or run with it to the wing to cross for a team-mate.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog50&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=50}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;We didn't need anyone else up front,&quot; Hurley later said. &quot;They couldn't get the ball off him. He was one of those guys who could beat five players easily.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog74&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=74}}&lt;/ref&gt; Andrews agreed: &quot;once he'd got the ball it was almost impossible to get it off him.&quot;&lt;ref name=biog192/&gt;

Friday was known for giving his all in any game in which he played, no matter the circumstances. Hurley later said that Friday would often become furious at his team-mates for not trying their best, even in training.&lt;ref name=biog40/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog54&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| pages=54–55}}&lt;/ref&gt;  This strong drive to always win even extended to the use of physical intimidation to unsettle opposing players, leading contemporary critics to label him a &quot;villain&quot;.&lt;ref name=swecho19770418/&gt; Friday also employed the use of psychological tactics; aiming to spook opposing players, Friday would kiss them or fondle their testicles. Cardiff team-mate [[Paul Went]] recalled that these tricks would &quot;completely [[wiktionary:throw#Etymology 1|throw]]&quot; defenders and affect their concentration.&lt;ref name=&quot;biog160161&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| pages=160–161}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Although he was often criticised for the number of bookings and sendings-off he received, Friday believed he was justified to chase victory by any means, explaining his attitude in a 1977 interview: &quot;On the pitch I hate all opponents. I don't give a damn about anyone. People think I'm mad, a lunatic. I am a winner.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;biog192&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last1=McGuigan
| last2=Hewitt
| year=1997
| page=192}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;

