==Footnotes==
&lt;div class=&quot;references-small&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 90%&quot;&gt;
:A.&amp;nbsp;{{note|career}} 27 January 1974 (first Football League game)&lt;ref name=biog41/&gt; or 6 February 1974 (signed professionally)&lt;ref name=biog43/&gt; to 20 December 1977 (retired)&lt;ref name=biog175/&gt;
:B.&amp;nbsp;{{note label|lawrensonkitbag|B|a}}{{note label|lawrensonkitbag|B|b}} According to some recent sources, Friday defecated in Lawrenson's kit bag after being sent off. Contemporary reports from the ''[[South Wales Echo]]'' and London ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', a 1987 profile included in ''The Bluebirds'' and interviews included in ''The Greatest Footballer You Never Saw: The Robin Friday Story'', published in 1997, do not mention this, merely describing Friday's being sent off for kicking Lawrenson in the face and then leaving the ground.&lt;ref name=crooks45/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog174/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;mirror19771031&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
 | date = 1977-10-31
 | title = Cardiff hit by Welsh Wizard
 | page = 31
 | journal=Daily Mirror
 | publisher=Trinity Mirror
 | location = London}}&lt;/ref&gt; Sources reporting the story as true include [[Channel 4]], the ''Halifax Courier'' and ''[[Football365]]'', in August 2007, May 2009 and October 2010 respectively.&lt;ref name=&quot;badboys&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=10 footballing bad boys
|publisher=[[Channel 4]]
|location=London
|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/sports/10+footballing+bad+boys/704247.html
|date=2007-08-21
|accessdate=2011-04-20}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=f365/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;halifaxcourier&quot;&gt;{{cite news
|title=Holding out for a hero...
|url=http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/lifestyle/columnists/holding_out_for_a_hero_1_1931247
|work=Halifax Courier
|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]
|date=2009-05-22
|accessdate=2011-05-13}}&lt;/ref&gt; A ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' article from October 2010 mentions it as something Friday was &quot;rumoured to have done&quot;.&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt; Roger Titford's December 2010 work, ''The Legend of Robin Friday'', categorically denies that it happened and gives the story's original source as &quot;some punk football T-shirt website&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Titford46&quot;&gt;{{cite book
| last=Titford
| page=46
| year=2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
:C.&amp;nbsp;{{note|goaltranmere}} No video footage of the goal exists. The description and account of the goal is based on contemporary newspaper match reports from the ''[[Reading Post|Reading Evening Post]]'' and London ''Daily Mirror'', as well as on accounts by the referee, [[Clive Thomas]], and three spectators of the match: Reading F.C. historian David Downs, Alf Friday and Syd Simmonds.&lt;ref name=roughley/&gt;&lt;ref name=Hewitt/&gt;&lt;ref name=honoured/&gt;&lt;ref name=biog130/&gt;&lt;ref name=mirror19760401/&gt;
:D.&amp;nbsp;{{note|cupfinal}} [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] won 4–2 on aggregate; Cardiff had won the first leg 2–1 on 16 May 1977 at [[Ninian Park]] with Friday scoring their second goal.&lt;ref name=biog171/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;welshcup&quot;&gt;{{Cite web
| url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal77.html
| title = Wales (Cup) 1976/77
| first = Dinant
| last = Abbink
| publisher = [[RSSSF|Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]
| accessdate = 2011-07-03
}}&lt;/ref&gt;
:E.&amp;nbsp;{{note|welsh}} The [[Welsh Cup]] is contested only by teams based in (or near) Wales.
